TY  - Inproceedings
TI  - EXTREME COASTAL DYNAMICS OF SITTAUNG ESTUARY (MYANMAR)
JO  - NANA
PY  - 2020
VL  - NA
IS  - NA
AB  - The Sittaung Estuary in Myanmar is the northern boundary of the Gulf of Mottama, where the outflow of the Sittaung river interacts with the tides in the Gulf of Mottama. The banks of this estuary experience cycles of extreme erosion rates, of up to 1.6 km/y, which forces local communities to abandon their villages and farms, while elsewhere in the estuary accretion and growth of tidal flats allows for the development of new agricultural land. As part of the Gulf of Mottama Project, we analyzed the rates of coastal erosion, studied the causes for the extreme dynamics and proposed adaptation strategies. Shoreline locations have been mapped from satellite images. Two field campaigns provided data on tidal channel depths and flow velocities. A numerical model of the estuary provided insight in the flow dynamics during the dry and wet season and allowed testing of potential measures. We found that the erosion predominantly results from the natural buildup and migration of bars and associated tidal channel migration (bar push); at other locations bank pull dominates the erosion processes. Moreover, channels are typically too small for the tidal prism, which results in extreme flow velocities. There are no human factors involved in the observed dynamics. A full stop or reduction of shoreline retreat may be achieved with traditional engineering measures with rock or concrete on the channel slopes and banks. Alternatively, Building with Nature type of interventions can be considered for example using vegetation on tidal flats or strategic sediment dredging and dumping, because they reduce tidal prism. However, none of the considered measures are considered cost-benefit effective, because the required investments exceed by far the economic value of the protected assets. The extreme and globally unique morphodynamic behavior of the Sittaung estuary is predictable on the short-term (< 5y), which means that adaptive use of the land, i.e. managed coastal retreat and managed coastal expansion, seems a most viable alternative. To support local communities, this may be facilitated by mobile infrastructure and accommodations, adequate monitoring of the actual shoreline development and communication with the local communities as part of an (adaptive) strategy for Bago Region and Mon State.
DO  - 10.1007/978-981-15-0291-0\_163
SN  - NA
KW  - erosion; tide; estuary; numerical modelling; coastal protection; adaptation strategies
