AB  - In this article, we explore some of the factors that have led to reductions in risk to climate-related hazards in two very distinct sites: the Cayman Islands in the Caribbean and the state of Ceara in NE Brazil. We find that a range of factors have been critical to reduce risk in both regions. These include: (a) flexible, responsive governance (b) committed and politically active actors; (c) disaster risk management integrated into other social and economic policy processes and (d) a long-term commitment to managing risk. The authors argue that reducing risk is an important foundation for building adaptive capacity among the poorest segments of society. The features of good disaster risk reduction can act as markers of good governance that are conducive to the design and implementation of deeper structural reform needed to address the root causes of vulnerability.
