VL  - NA
IS  - NA
AB  - Southeast Asia, an economically, geographically, and culturally diverse region with a population of about 600 million, is a key stakeholder in moving towards a regional and global climate smart future. Indonesia is the largest economy in Southeast Asia and is the worldâ€™s fourth most populous nation with a citizenry of 245 million. Although the majority of Indonesians now live in cities, it is still a developing country with an annual growth of 5 to 6 percent. Politically, it is transitioning from a planned economy to one that is based on market principles. As an archipelagic country consisting of 17, 000 low-lying islands, Indonesia faces multiple threats from climate change, particularly along its 80, 000 km of coastlines. Not only does 60 percent of the population live in coastal cities, much of Indonesiaâ€™s infrastructure and fertile agricultural lands are in these low-lying regions. Climate change-induced floods and droughts, receding coastlines, saltwater intrusion, and land submergence are impeding efforts to reduce poverty and food insecurity, threatening livelihoods and biodiversity and spreading diseases including malaria, dengue, cholera, and diarrhea. In many respects, Indonesiaâ€™s challenges are similar to those faced by other Asian countries like China and India: poverty, limited energy resources, pollution, and the growing impacts of climate change. Yet, for Indonesia and other Southeast Asian economies, the bulk of their greenhouse gas (GHG) emissions that cause climate change are not primarily from the consumption of energy but from land use, land use change and forestry (LULUCF) and peat fires. Indonesiaâ€™s National Council on Climate Change reports that the degradation and destruction of peatlands and forests accounts for 41 percent and 37 percent, respectively, of Indonesiaâ€™s 2.3GTCO Accordingly, forest management related issues have received great attention with regard to mitigation of GHG emissions in Indonesia. Indonesiaâ€™s signing of a letter of intent with Norway in May 2010 for $1 billion in grant financing to support programs leading to reductions in GHG emissions from deforestation, forest degradation and peat land conversion is indeed a major milestone in such efforts. In addition, several other development partners including Australia, Germany, Japan, UK and USA targeted their climate change assistance to the forestry and land use sector in Indonesia. The degradation of forests is threatening Indonesiaâ€™s environmental and socio- economic sustainability. Over 16 million people live in forests, which also help to protect freshwater supplies by stabilizing soil on hill slopes and regulating the speed and timing of river flow. Wildfires in these forests are becoming more frequent, leading to dangerous levels of particulate pollution. These watersheds have already lost 20 percent of their forest cover between 1985 and 1997 and continue to be logged and harvested for timber. With high levels of poverty and unemployment over 15 percent (Depsos 2009), developing economies like Indonesia cannot afford to sacrifice economic growth to reduce GHG emissions. Indonesia has identified three main principles to move towards a low carbon, climate resilient economy (LCE): (1) the climate change response strategy cannot be separated from long-term national development strategy; (2) the principle of equity and justice must guide the process of anticipating and assessing the impact; and (3) net GHG emissions must be reduced without hampering national development objectives. Â© 2012 selection and editorial material, Ancha Srinivasan, Frank Hiroshi Ling and Hideyuki Mori; individual chapters, the contributors.
