TY  - Article
TI  - Saving Yucatan's coast: Geotextile tubes stabilize shores in Mexico
JO  - Geotechnical Fabrics Report
PY  - 2005
VL  - 23
IS  - 7
AB  - The project team set out to restore the original, natural conditions regarding littoral drift as it was before human action. First, all perpendicular groins that had been developed were removed. A key point of the actions was to reestablish conditions that would generate the coast's natural dune, an element that is considered essential in any stabilized beach profile. A finely developed and vegetated dune becomes an excellent protection in extreme conditions (hurricanes), as well as a limit for the coastline regression process. Also, it allows equilibrated long shore sediments transport. Another design need was to avoid rigid defence structures. Since wave climate, bathymetry profiles, and sediment conditions are forever changing, the solution had to be as flexible as possible so it would absorb any physical media modification. Given these conditions, geosynthetics were considered optimal for the beach protection project. Woven polypropylene geotextile tubes were designed to work as a limit regression line, allowing the natural dune to be recovered. Also, they provided the performance flexibility that could dissipate wave energy so sediments would slow down-restoring the beach, while at the same time allowing enough movement of gains that adjacent beaches would not be affected.
