AB  - The Italian governmental organizations, including the Ministry of the Environment, and the local authorities, particularly Regions, have recently shown the tendency to diffuse coastal management programs conforming to the principle of sustainable development. In this framework, ENEA has been carrying out investigations aimed at contributing to the design of a national Coastal Master Plan. This approach could be regarded as the present step of an evolutionary political process, which started in 1982, when the Italian Parliament adopted the Sea Protection Act (Legge sulla difesa del mare). This paper aims to present this prospect and, more in detail, discuss some peculiarities of the Italian context. Furthermore, it will outline guidelines for Coastal Master Plan designing. The following issues will be discussed: (i) the general condition of the Italian coastal areas and small islands; (ii) the expected impact due to climate changes; (iii) the changing framework of coastal uses; (iv) the increasing and conflictual uses of coastal areas; (v) the role of legal and institutional frameworks; (vi) a tentative approach to Coastal Master Plan designing.
