TI  - Hurricane hazard mitigation in the Caribbean: Recent advances and present challenges
JO  - NANA
PY  - 1998
VL  - NA
IS  - NA
AB  - Over the past two decades, the Caribbean region has experienced a dramatic upsurge in the level of destruction caused by hurricanes and tropical storms. Recent increases in activity are consistent with the inter-decadal variation in hurricane activity, and may also be influenced by Global Climate Change. Starting with the Pan Caribbean Disaster Preparedness and Prevention Project (PCDPPP) in the early 1980's, the Caribbean has benefited from a series of regional programmes which have contributed to an increased awareness and better understanding of the hazard and risk associated with tropical cyclones. Under the coordination of the Caribbean Disaster and Emergency Response Agency (CDERA), national emergency management offices in each country are being strengthened and are expanding their responsibilities beyond preparedness and response. Since 1993, the Caribbean Disaster Mitigation Project (CDMP) has supported several advances in the assessment of hurricane hazards and in the design of specific interventions aimed at reducing the vulnerability of housing and lifeline infrastructure. Numerical modeling and simulation of the physical dynamics of tropical weather systems, and statistical determination of return periods for tropical events have greatly improved the range and reliability of information for emergency management and for coastal land use planning and infrastructure design. In addition to supporting technical initiatives based on engineering studies, the CDMP has focused its efforts on building institutional capacity, technology transfer and public education about disaster mitigation. Partnerships have been established with CDERA, the Caribbean Meteorological Institute, the Caribbean Development Bank, the insurance industry and several national development foundations to implement a variety of vulnerability reduction initiatives in housing, community development, schools and shelters, and public infrastructure. Changing the attitude of Caribbean governments and people about disaster mitigation remains a major challenge. By effectively demonstrating that mitigation represents a small fraction of the initial cost of a project, the CDMP is aiming at fully integrating disaster risk reduction into the development planning and investment decision making process in the region.
