AB  - This paper presents a summary of the physical processes involved in the rapidly eroding shoreline along the North Tidal Channel at the inlet to Willapa Bay, Washington, near the city of North Cove. The major causes of erosion at North Cove were shown to be northward migration of the deep North Tidal Channel and wave energy. A multi-purpose groin is described that was designed, in conjunction with beach nourishment, to dissipate wave energy and protect Washington State Road 105. An underwater dike designed to prevent northward migration of the North Tidal Channel is also described. Monitoring of the pre-project and post-project physical conditions in the project area are discussed.
