TI  - Relocation of a tidal channel for shore stabilization and protection
JO  - NANA
PY  - 1999
VL  - NA
IS  - NA
AB  - In 1997, a large, meandering marginal tidal channel located along the northern end of Hilton Head Island, South Carolina USA was relocated away from a developed shoreline for purposes of shore stabilization and upland protection. The channel and an associated shoal system has been migrating toward the shoreline for at least the past 25 years, but until recently did not pose a threat to the upland development. At the time of the relocation, the channel had eroded the entire intertidal beach platform along a 300-meter section of shoreline and exposed the developed upland bluff to extreme erosional forces. Channel relocation was the only feasible alternative to protect the upland properties-due to the fact that other shore protection alternatives, such as large sandbags or hard coastal structures (i.e., seawall and revetments) are not permittable in the State of South Carolina. The project included the excavation and transport of 295,000 cubic meters of material from the new ``pilot{''} channel to the existing channel meander. The project was successfully completed in 7 days.
